Acknowledge that where claimants are victims of colonisation, the objects subject to claim may be a stand in for the broader negative affects of colonial rule on their community; symbolic, about the culture and violence done to them, not the object itself

Q: could increased regulation of the art market help improve transparency? Already regulated, trend towards greater regulation of privacy. Licit and illicit objects moving through the same channels, hard to differentiate. Valid reasons for privacy in transactions

Not much diversity in museums, particularly at curatorial level. Museums talk about communities being hard to reach, but is it really that museums/their communities are hard to enter? Ongoing, time-consuming, and expensive process to rectify
Lots of talk around restitution is sensible. Why are we not mobilising in support of local diaspora communities - and amplifying their voices?
And now back to the room for coffee and further discussion!
Displayed under 'Victorians' - with a very safe consideration of empire here, doesn't mention e g. the Opium Wars.

Indian gold amulet here in the Money Gallery. Came with a 19thC label, confirming that it was 'looted' during the Indian Mutiny (which the current label says was 'crushed'). We don't know which palace it came from. Requires reinterpretation - language important

Doesn't claim to be representative, but about to start. This is a temporary installation, put up May 2019, soon to come down. Previous display (18thC table lay) will go back but with different interpretation with input from the community - keep this narrative present

Here looking at tea, sugar linked to slavery, a tale that is not usually told in the gallery. Many of the people working on the installation had been on the Windrush. Nearby recordings show these people telling their stories. More about process than end product

'A Nice Cup of Tea?' installation in the European Ceramics gallery as an example of co-curation, part of the 'Ashmolean for All' initiative engaging with communities not usually represented in the visitor demographics. https://t.co/hSpobhgK6f
Here is the ivory panel and the information provided in the gallery https://t.co/qtF7KGYDut
https://t.co/CoSishIq1a

They restituted it to Mannheim's widow. She gave it to the head of the Jesuit order in Oxford, since he had helped her. The Dutch government still had a claim on it; in 1953 she had to pay the object's value to the Dutch gov so she could keep it and give it

Bank vault where it was stored was destroyed during the Blitz, and this object picked up by an Irish sailor, who traded it for drinks in a pub in Cork! Eventually came up on market in Dublin in 1940s, acquired by Mr and Mrs Hunt, who recognised it from Burlington Magazine

Small piece on loan from Campion Hall, said to have belonged to Mary Queen of Scots. Offered for sale by family in Germany in 1920s, later bought by Fritz Mannheimer in 1936. He sent some of his collection to London before war broke out, and committed suicide https://t.co/ySELSzoQid
This ewer was previously returned to the family in 1956, then sold by them in New York, and later acquired by Wellby before coming to the Ashmolean.

Also a serpentine ewer and basin in this gallery. Wellby's catalogue provided provenance from collection of founder of Dresden Bank. Museum actively notified Spoliation Committee of the object when they received it, and knew an heir survived in California

The committee concluded it should not be returned to the heirs. Bittersweet conclusion for the museum. The claimants were not direct descendants, which may have made a difference to the outcome. There is now an explanatory sheet in the gallery providing the story of the object

An ivory panel showing people playing chess was subject to a claim, and referred to the Spoliation Committee. Main question over whether the sale was forced; difficult to prove since the owner had been hit by the depression in 1920s, and it reached a fair price at sale
Very interesting collection in terms of authenticity as well as provenance - research is ongoing

Ashmolean accepted whole collection knowing they would have a number of claims. Museum knew Michael was legal owner of all objects, so heirs could only claim if the objects came into a public museum. One mid-16thC salt cellar has already been returned to heirs in 2014(since sold)

Wellby kept some objects in a cabinet in his house. Ashmolean considered a safe and sensitive repository. At the time of him buying, regarded as 'bad manners' to ask a dealer where the acquired something. Museum knew some objects likely to have been moved due to Holocaust
Now to the Michael Wellby gallery. Emeritus curator Timothy Wilson tells us about its design as a 'little green vault' in Oxford (as in Dresden) https://t.co/M8birqGrHL

Spoliation panel concluded sale was legitimate and not forced. Came to the Ashmolean in 1968 from William Spooner, who bought it innocently in 1930s. The heirs' legal advisor probably cost more than the picture worth - but morality more important than financial value

Next up: painting owned by collector Jacob Goldschmidt, sold 1936. His heirs claimed this was a forced sale as the collector was Jewish, and sold well below market price. Ashmolean claimed sold 1936 following agreement 1932 after collapse of bank Goldschmidt involved with https://t.co/NchwmDlA3S
Here is a picture of 'Looty'! https://t.co/pcw3Hvndbd

The old tapestry label did describe the piece as being looted, but did not mention the Opium Wars. Suggested that the new label may include also be printed in mandarin - the museum receives many Chinese visitors
This was taken from the Summer Palace, which was burned down in retaliation by Western forces in 1860. At the same time a number of Pekinese dogs were taken, including one later called 'Looty'!

Starting our tour of objects in the Ashmolean led by curator Matthew Winterbottom, here in the West meets East gallery discussing a tapestry from China, soon to be rehung in the gallery https://t.co/SKiKhoXxUu

Duccio panel example could be considered for repatriation but is usually not. Context of postcolonial society; e.g. Ethiopian objects displayed and preserved in London benefitting Ethiopian community in London

Museums must be sensitive to these different relationships that visitors may have with objects on display. Sometimes e.g. guides may (unknowingly) provide incorrect information about sensitive objects, which is a form of disrespect

Not all contested objects are art objects, e.g. relics, objects of active use and cultural or religious value. The same context cannot be created outside the original setting. This could also apply to e.g. Duccio devotional picture
